<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-06T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-06T13:00:00-05:00" n="955" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d955">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72111/280</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-06T18:00:00+00:00">
                                <hi rend="italic">August 6, 1914, 6 p.m.</hi>
                            </date>
                            <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 5:30 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>287. The British Admiralty state to naval attaché that German ships are
                            leaving American ports constantly, provisioned and armed to prey on
                            British commerce, and that British Government will undoubtedly claim
                            full value for vessels destroyed or captured by such German ships. Such
                            a claim may run into enormous sums.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>